reviews.review_text: Amazing I still can't believe no one has any insight into this band we know as the grateful dead. Any insight to write about anyway. Ill continue to write. How you like Donna in this one? Any one? Peace. Stay immortal dead.

A Pristine Version - All-timer Show! I'm just deeply experiencing, currently in St. Stephen, this show like I've never heard it before. And I have. I had Charlie's excellent version, obtained just this past June of '20, having been fully sucked down the '76 rabbit hole after the release of the June '76 Box Set. But I lost it, in a storage issue dispute with my Mac. Now resolved, I went looking for this to download to my Christmas gift of an external hd. This is the version I found elsewhere, and after reading the comments, and seeing Charlie's blessing of this version, went for it. It is pristine! Like in all-caps! I'm listening on headphones and I'm floating somehow between each of the guys. Phenomenal sound. And this show...it's surprising to me it doesn't get mentioned more in those "best of" discussions. I know the shows surrounding it, the Orpheum run, are all considered good to great. This though? This has that je ne sais quoi. Special.

Jaw dropped Charlie - Thank you SO MUCH!  For everything you do and the countless hours of joy you've given to me, and to us all.  But this one...It's the pearl of '76, imo.  Espectially that second set which is nothing short of sublime.  The orignal FM broadcast isn't great and a solid board hasn't popped that wasn't flawed in some way...until now.  You polished this one so beautifully.  I'm so beyond thrilled as this is a top 5 show of all time for me.  Over the years we've gotten the pitch correction, noise reduction, and now hum reduction.  It feels like I'm there, finally.  Decades passed awaiting this.  Just, wow.  Thank you sir!!

Yes This is a great recording of a classic show. Charlie Miller always does great work, although I have to say that I often disagree with his decisions on where to split up the tracks.

In this recording, around 14:30 of Let It Grow, it starts to sound very much like a long intro to Wharf Rat, so I would split the track there and include it in Wharf Rat.. Similarly, at around 13:20 of Wharf Rat, it begins to sound very clearly like the intro to The Other One, so I would split the track there. But that's just me.
